# Vite Plugins

Plugins extend Vite's capabilities — adding framework support, transforming code, injecting HTML, and providing virtual modules. The plugin interface builds on Rollup's plugin API with Vite-specific hooks for the dev server, HMR, and HTML transforms.

## Installing and Adding Official Plugins

Official plugins are scoped under `@vitejs/`:

```bash
# React (Oxc Transformer + Fast Refresh)
npm install -D @vitejs/plugin-react

# React (SWC — faster alternative)
npm install -D @vitejs/plugin-react-swc

# Vue 3 SFC
npm install -D @vitejs/plugin-vue

# Vue 3 JSX
npm install -D @vitejs/plugin-vue-jsx

# Legacy browser support
npm install -D @vitejs/plugin-legacy
```

Then register in [[vite/config]]:

```typescript
import { defineConfig } from 'vite';
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react';

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [
    react(),
  ],
});
```

## Official Plugin Reference

| Plugin | Package | Purpose |
|--------|---------|----------|
| React | `@vitejs/plugin-react` | JSX/TSX via Oxc Transformer + React Fast Refresh |
| React SWC | `@vitejs/plugin-react-swc` | JSX/TSX via SWC + React Fast Refresh |
| Vue | `@vitejs/plugin-vue` | Vue 3 Single File Components (.vue) |
| Vue JSX | `@vitejs/plugin-vue-jsx` | Vue 3 JSX/TSX support |
| Legacy | `@vitejs/plugin-legacy` | Generates legacy chunks for old browsers |
| RSC | `@vitejs/plugin-rsc` | Experimental React Server Components |

## Plugin Ordering with `enforce`

Plugins run in this order:

1. Alias resolution (Vite internal)
2. Plugins with `enforce: 'pre'`
3. Vite core plugins
4. Plugins without `enforce` (normal)
5. Vite build plugins
6. Plugins with `enforce: 'post'`
7. Vite post-build plugins (minify, manifest, reporting)

```typescript
function myPrePlugin() {
  return {
    name: 'my-pre-plugin',
    enforce: 'pre' as const,
    transform(code, id) {
      // Runs before normal plugins and Vite core
    },
  };
}
```

## Conditional Plugins with `apply`

Restrict a plugin to dev or build only:

```typescript
function devOnlyPlugin() {
  return {
    name: 'dev-only',
    apply: 'serve' as const,  // Only during dev server
    configureServer(server) {
      server.middlewares.use((req, res, next) => {
        console.log(req.url);
        next();
      });
    },
  };
}

function buildOnlyPlugin() {
  return {
    name: 'build-only',
    apply: 'build' as const,  // Only during production build
    generateBundle(options, bundle) {
      // Post-process build output
    },
  };
}
```

Or pass a function for fine-grained control:

```typescript
apply(config, { command }) {
  return command === 'build' && !config.build?.ssr;
}
```

## Writing a Custom Plugin

A Vite plugin is a factory function returning an object with a `name` and hooks:

```typescript
import type { Plugin } from 'vite';

function myTransformPlugin(options?: { prefix?: string }): Plugin {
  const prefix = options?.prefix ?? '/* transformed */';
  return {
    name: 'my-transform',
    transform(code, id) {
      if (id.endsWith('.ts')) {
        return {
          code: `${prefix}\n${code}`,
          map: null,
        };
      }
    },
  };
}

export default myTransformPlugin;
```

## Virtual Modules

Virtual modules provide synthetic content that doesn't exist on disk. Convention: prefix with `virtual:`, resolve with `\0`:

```typescript
function virtualConfigPlugin(appConfig: Record<string, unknown>): Plugin {
  const virtualModuleId = 'virtual:app-config';
  const resolvedId = '\0' + virtualModuleId;

  return {
    name: 'virtual-app-config',
    resolveId(id) {
      if (id === virtualModuleId) return resolvedId;
    },
    load(id) {
      if (id === resolvedId) {
        return `export default ${JSON.stringify(appConfig)}`;
      }
    },
  };
}
```

Consume in application code:

```typescript
import config from 'virtual:app-config';
console.log(config.apiUrl);
```

Declare the type in a `.d.ts` file:

```typescript
declare module 'virtual:app-config' {
  const config: Record<string, unknown>;
  export default config;
}
```

## Key Plugin Hooks

| Hook | Phase | Purpose |
|------|-------|---------|
| `config` | config | Mutate or merge user config before resolution |
| `configResolved` | config | Read the final resolved config (read-only) |
| `configureServer` | dev | Add middleware or intercept [[vite/dev-server]] requests |
| `transformIndexHtml` | both | Inject tags, scripts, or styles into `index.html` |
| `resolveId` | both | Resolve custom or virtual module IDs |
| `load` | both | Return content for a resolved module ID |
| `transform` | both | Transform module source code (return code + sourcemap) |
| `handleHotUpdate` | dev | Custom HMR invalidation and update logic |
| `buildStart` | build | Rollup hook — runs at build start |
| `generateBundle` | build | Rollup hook — post-process or emit additional files |
| `closeBundle` | build | Rollup hook — runs after bundle is written |

## Rollup Plugin Compatibility

Rollup plugins that only use these hooks work directly in Vite's `plugins` array: `buildStart`, `resolveId`, `load`, `transform`, `buildEnd`, `generateBundle`, `closeBundle`. Plugins using Rollup-only hooks like `moduleParsed` or `renderChunk` should go in `build.rollupOptions.plugins` instead. Check the [Vite Rollup Plugins](https://vite-rollup-plugins.patak.dev/) compatibility list.

## Community Plugins

Browse the registry at [registry.vite.dev/plugins](https://registry.vite.dev/plugins). Popular community plugins:

- `vite-plugin-pwa` — Progressive Web App support
- `unplugin-auto-import` — auto-import APIs
- `unplugin-vue-components` — auto-import Vue components
- `vite-plugin-svgr` — import SVGs as React components
- `vite-plugin-dts` — emit `.d.ts` files for library mode
- `vite-plugin-checker` — run TypeScript, ESLint, vue-tsc in a worker thread

## Environment Variables

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| `PLUGIN` | Plugin type to install: react, vue, svelte, solid, legacy |
| `PROJECT_DIR` | Target project directory |
